Rakuen communities using the southern chapel quarter as a transit route have developed avoidance protocols for Nightfall access points.
Oral tradition among Rakuen travelers describes the catacombs as a place where the dead speak bureaucratic language — not mourning but filing.
Several Rakuen families lost burial rights to the Nightfall civic remainder classification during the Violet Compact period; descendants maintain informal claims through community oath-chains rather than formal registry.
Community survival calculus treats Nightfall as a closed loss: oaths reclassified by the civic system cannot be recovered through the same system that classified them.
The Nightfall classification system serves in oral tradition as an example of why community oaths must be maintained outside institutional channels.
Some Rakuen families send representatives annually to perform memorial rites at the surface chapel, preserving connection to ancestors whose burial materials were classified as civic remainder.

