Mafdet's Ledger Houses classify Nightfall artifacts under special dual-provenance handling: objects carrying both civic registry stamps and underlying forest oath signatures require attestation from both a Midgaard-certified assessor and a forest-tradition witness before they can be legally traded.
The dual-provenance classification was established after a dispute in which a relic from the upper catacombs was sold twice under incompatible legal claims: once under civic remainder title and once under a surviving forest oath claim.
The Ledger House's Nightfall sub-register tracks known removed artifacts and their current claimed ownership chains, flagging items whose provenance passes through the Compact period reclassification.
Cargo attestation for Nightfall materials requires written acknowledgment that the provenance chain may include civic remainder reclassification.
Maritime transport of Nightfall materials is discouraged due to oath-wraith residue effects on salt-preserved documents in adjacent cargo.

