---
From Umbral perspective, the Catacombs of Nightfall are notable for what is absent: the shadow-record of what was reclassified rather than preserved.
Umbral assessment distinguishes deliberate concealment from procedural erasure; Nightfall represents the latter — records overwritten rather than hidden, leaving a shadow-archive of displaced content.
The deeper tiers contain shadow-impressions of forest oath materials: the shapes left by their absence after civic remainder reclassification.
Umbral-sensitive observers report a deeper layer of impression-entities performing the reclassification record's function in the shadow layer.
Umbral navigation is complicated by crossed shadow-records: civic registry impressions overlaying forest oath shadows, creating interference that disrupts shadow-movement.
The Nightfall shadow layer is one of the densest institutional-shadow sites near Midgaard, more complex than the Gloamvault because the reclassification accumulated through procedural momentum rather than design.

flags MIDGAARD USHABTI
---
Ushabti cosmic law assessment centers on jurisdictional illegitimacy: the Violet Compact applied administrative authority to materials whose legal status was settled under prior oath law.
Cosmic law recognizes oath obligations as binding regardless of reclassification; a forest oath filed as civic remainder remains active under cosmic jurisprudence even if void under civil code.
This creates what Ushabti scholars call an unresolved cosmic docket: cases administratively closed but cosmically open.
The oath-wraith population enforces these obligations — jurisdictional agents under pre-civic authority never superseded.
Dispersing oath-wraiths without resolving the docket destroys agents without closing their cases — a cosmic law violation.
Proper resolution requires cosmic law closure (voiding oaths through oath-dissolution) or civic correction (restoring reclassified materials to proper status). Neither has been pursued because both require acknowledging the reclassification's illegitimacy.
